You may review all disclosures relating to your accounts by returning to the Fidelity.com classic experience or logging on to NetBenefits.com.
    
						
     "All Accounts" equals the sum of the balances of the selected accounts identified in the account selector. These accounts may include your Fidelity personal and workplace accounts (excluding pension benefits), accounts managed by a third party adviser but held at Fidelity, and accounts accessible via the Full View service (identified as non-Fidelity accounts, if you have signed up for this service). Pension benefits are not included. Workplace account balances may include unvested amounts. Fidelity Charitable  Giving Account  balances are owned and held by Fidelity Charitable , an independent public charity with a donor-advised fund program, and therefore such balances are not included in All Accounts. Giving Account  balances are displayed as a convenience for Fidelity Charitable's donors who are also Fidelity customers. Information regarding non-Fidelity accounts that are denominated in foreign currency or that hold positions in foreign currency may be  displayed on this page in USD.  You may view information for non-Fidelity accounts in its original foreign denomination using the FullView service.  Fidelity is not able to verify the accuracy, timeliness or completeness of information regarding accounts accessible via the Full View service.
    
						
    This information is provided as a convenience and is not a substitute for your Fidelity account statement, nor is it intended for trading purposes. Please consult your account statement, and any statements from the respective financial institution for the accounts provided for information regarding your account balance, positions, and transactions. This information may include assets that Fidelity does not hold on your behalf and which are obtained through the Full View service.
    
						
    Workplace Savings accounts reported as of the end of the day: [02/12/2019]
    						
						
    Securities are priced real-time for customers that have agreed to the Real-Time Quotes Subscriber Agreements; otherwise, quotes are delayed at least 15 minutes. If the current market price is unavailable or the market is closed, Fidelity will factor in the most recent closing market price to determine the closing market value.
    
						
    Account balances containing only mutual fund positions or portfolios that are included in College Savings accounts are updated less frequently as they rely on transaction settlement periods for when money or shares are bought, sold, or transferred. Mutual fund distributions and capital gains can affect your account value and typically have a 1-3 business day settlement period before your account is updated.
    
						
    College Savings Portfolios are calculated using the prior business day's closing price.
    
						
    Annuities are priced as of the market close date on which the value per unit, income value, or withdrawal value for an annuity was last calculated.
    
						
    # Annuity values do not reflect pending transactions. Final values will be posted later.
    
						
    ++ Income and Payout Annuity contracts are not included in your total account value.
    
						
    Balances and holdings displayed for non-Fidelity accounts reflect information available on your account sites when last refreshed (including information from accounts that are denominated in foreign currency or that hold positions in foreign currency from your non-Fidelity accounts, if available). You may view information for non-Fidelity accounts in its original foreign denomination using the Full View service. Non-Fidelity account aggregation services provided by Yodlee, Inc., an independent company not affiliated with Fidelity Investments.
    
						
    Balances displayed for your accounts and positions reflect information available when your selected accounts were last refreshed. If you manually refresh only some of your accounts, the values shown for the positions in those accounts and the balances shown in the Account Selector for those accounts may be more up to date than accounts/positions that were not manually refreshed.
						 Accrued interest balances, if displayed, are as of the end of the prior business day.
    
						
    Amount collected and available for immediate withdrawal. This balance includes both Core and other Fidelity Money Market funds held in each account listed within Manage Money & Payments. This balance does not include deposits that have not cleared. Sell orders are reflected in this balance on settlement date and Buy orders are reflected on trade date. Note: Within Manage Money & Payments charts, Health Savings Accounts (HSAs) are included in the non-IRA categories for Core and Non-Core Money Market Funds.
    
						
    The Stock Plans values displayed are arrived at using the prior business day closing price, or the cash value for cash based plans. Please refer to the provisions in your individual Award Agreement and the official stock plan document which govern the terms of your award. The provisions in the Award Agreement and stock plan document supercede any information, including conflicting information, reflected on the website.

    Personal Rate of Return is calculated with a time-weighted formula, widely used by financial analysts to calculate investment earnings. The calculated value reflects the result of your investment selections as well as any activity in the plan accounts shown. Other personal rate of return formulas may yield different results. Remember, past performance is no guarantee of future results.
    					
					
    
					
    
						
    Personal Rate of Return information for authorized Fidelity accounts will become available the monthly cycle following authorization. For periods less than one year, performance returns are presented on a cumulative basis.
    
						
    If your return information contains dashes '--', we either don't have a return for that time period, or your account is being validated. Accounts opened after the beginning of the year are excluded from the calculation.
    
						
    Your Personal Rate of Return is calculated using a money-weighted formula. It reflects the performance of the underlying investments in your eligible Fidelity accounts including dividends, interest, and fees; as well as the size and timing of your individual trades. If you use an account with cash management features, the Personal Rate of Return calculation may be affected by deposits, withdrawals, bill payment and other money movement transactions. Non-Fidelity accounts are excluded from the calculation. The Personal Rate of Return is an estimate only and should not be used solely in making investment decisions. It is calculated using Fidelity-provided information and information from third-party data sources and providers and therefore Fidelity cannot make any representations or guarantees as to its timeliness and accuracy. Fidelity will not provide notification that past data may have been inaccurate, or that it has been corrected.
    
						
    Personal Rate of Return (money-weighted) information may not be available for the following account types: Employer-Sponsored Retirement Plans (e.g., 401(k) plans), Brokerage Link accounts, Brokerage Flex accounts, certain insurance/annuity holdings, and stock plans. These accounts are also not included in the Rate of Return calculation for your entire portfolio appearing at the top of the Portfolio Summary page. Time-weighted returns are available for Employer-Sponsored Retirement Plans as of the end of the previous business day and can be accessed by See YTD Change link.
    
						
    Performance calculations include accounts that have been "hidden" since the last performance reporting period. "Hidden" accounts will be removed from all performance calculations during the next monthly update.
    
						
    Returns shown for periods that include company stock plan transactions typically start at the time of purchase, exercise or vesting. Please refer to Help/Glossary for more information.

    Today's Gain/Loss equals the total dollar change in securities held for the selected accounts identified in the account selector. This balance only factors in securities held and does not include any pending activity (debits/credits) within the selected accounts. The percentage change represents the total dollar change compared to the value of securities held in your accounts, not the total account value.
    
						
    Today's Gain/Loss does not include 529 CIT accounts, Annuity contracts, non-Fidelity accounts, workplace accounts or pension benefits listed in the All Accounts view.
    
						
    For securities priced daily, such as mutual funds, Today's Gain/Loss is calculated using the prior business day's market closing price. For securities priced intraday, Today's Gain/Loss is calculated using the last available price.
    
						
					
    
					
    
						
    Your Balance Over Time reflects the difference in your All Accounts total balance over the selected time period. It includes all gain, loss, deposit and withdrawal activity over the selected time period, as of the most recent market close. This difference is divided by the beginning total balance at the start of the selected time period to calculate the relevant percentage increase or decrease during this time period.
    
						
    All Accounts equals the sum of the balances of the selected accounts identified in the account selector. These accounts may include your Fidelity personal and workplace accounts, accounts managed by a third party adviser but held at Fidelity, and accounts accessible via the Full View service (identified as non-Fidelity accounts, if you have signed up for this service). Information regarding non-Fidelity accounts that are denominated in foreign currency or that hold positions in foreign currency may be displayed on this page in USD. You may view information for non-Fidelity accounts in its original foreign denomination using the FullView service. Fidelity is not able to verify the accuracy, timeliness or completeness of information regarding accounts accessible via the Full View service.
    
						
    This information is provided as a convenience and is not a substitute for your Fidelity account statement, nor is it intended for trading purposes. Please consult your account statement, and any statements from the respective financial institution for the accounts provided for information regarding your account balance, positions, and transactions. This information may include assets that Fidelity does not hold on your behalf and which are obtained through the Full View service.
    
					
    
					
    
						
    Your Allocation Style is determined based on the rounded percentage of equity holdings in your selected accounts as follows:
						
      
							
    • if equity % is less than or equal to 10%, then Short Term;
      • 
							
    • if equity % is between 11% - 24%, then Conservative;
      • 
							
    • if equity % is between 25% - 34%, then Moderate With Income;
      • 
							
    • if equity % is between 35% - 44%, then Moderate;
      •  
							
    • if equity % is between 45% - 54%, then Balanced;
      • 
							
    • if equity % is between 55% - 64%, then Growth With Income;
      • 
							
    • if equity % is between 65% - 78%, then Growth;
      • 
							
    • if equity % is between 79% - 92%, then Aggressive Growth;
      • 
							
    • if equity % is greater than or equal to 93% then Most Aggressive;
      • 
						
    
						
    If a large portion of your holdings are identified as Unknown or Other, the percentage of equity holdings in your selected accounts may be low, indicating a low level of risk associated with your portfolio, without consideration of the risks associated with the Unknown and Other assets. As a result, your asset allocation assessment may not accurately reflect the current risks inherent in your selected accounts.
    
						
    Note: For purposes of this asset allocation analysis, generally, the underlying investments held in a mutual fund, other pooled investment vehicle or sub-account of a variable annuity are considered individually. They are separated and sorted into whichever asset class they best fit based on holdings data provided by a third party vendor. If holdings data is not available to Fidelity, the interest is categorized as Unknown. The Other category includes non -asset class holdings (i.e., identified holdings that cannot be categorized as stocks, bonds or short-term investments). For additional details, please refer to the Glossary of Terms.
    
						
    
							
    Long positions are those reported securities holdings held individually or as underlying investments that were fully paid purchases. Short positions are those margin or short positions held individually or as underlying investments that were not fully paid purchases, but instead involved borrowing in order to support the purchase. Note that trades initiated within a money market fund (such as Fidelity Cash Reserves) pending settlement at the close of a calendar month may present as a short position or negative allocation and inadvertently impact the analysis set forth above. The chart provides an approximate indication of these types of holdings.
    
						
    
					
    
					
    
						
    Securities are priced real-time for customers that have agreed to the Real-Time Quotes Subscriber Agreements; otherwise, quotes are delayed at least 15 minutes. If the current market price is unavailable or the market is closed, Fidelity will factor in the most recent closing market price to determine the closing market value. Non-Fidelity account positions totals may differ from the balances shown in your list of accounts because positions are updated more frequently than account balances.
    
						
    When Securities are Priced:
    
						
    Equities and ETFs are typically priced real-time. If the current market price is unavailable or the market is closed, Fidelity will factor in the most recent closing market price to determine the closing market value.
    
						
    Mutual fund positions are priced after the official market close (typically between 5 p.m. and 6 p.m. ET) at which point your account is calculated using the new price and current shares for that position. If a sale or purchase of a mutual fund settles that day, the account value will be calculated using the new quantity the following day. During market open, mutual fund positions are priced as of the previous day's market close.
    
						
    Annuities are priced as of the market close date on which the value per unit, income value, or withdrawal value for an annuity was last calculated. Annuity contract values reported on an individual basis. Click on the individual contract for details.
    
						
    If a trade has recently been made in your Fidelity  Personalized Portfolios account, the value of your positions after market hours may be calculated using the previous day's share quantity and may not accurately reflect the true market value of your positions at this time. Any changes to your position holdings will be updated in your account around 4 AM EST.
    
						
    For a detailed quote for a security, select the symbol link.  
    
						
    Consolidated real-time quotes and last price are displayed in all locations where you may enter and implement a trade with Fidelity; other sources of market data may be displayed on research and informational pages and screens.

    Fidelity will attempt to cancel an open or partially filled order on
						a "best efforts" basis. Because Fidelity is responsible for
						executing an order as promptly as possible upon receipt, your order may
						have been partially or completely filled before the cancellation was
						received and accepted.
    
						
    A single order for a large quantity of shares of a security may be
						filled through multiple executions. In some cases, not all of these
						executions are accessible on this page. To verify if the order has been
						filled in its entirety, please go to the "Positions" page or call a
						trading representative at 1-800-544-6666.
    
						
						
    Price improvement details provided for domestic stock and single leg option orders entered during market hours after the primary opening, provided there is a National Best Bid and Offer (NBBO) at the time the order is placed. Price improvement details are provided for informational purposes only and are not used for regulatory reporting purposes.
     

						
    Buy market orders with a weighted average execution price below the National Best Offer (NBO) are considered price improved. Price improvement for buy market orders is calculated by subtracting the weighted average execution price from the NBO, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on buy limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the NBO minus the execution price and the limit price minus the execution price. Sell market orders with a weighted average execution price above the National Best Bid (NBB) are considered price improved. Price improvement for sell market orders is calculated by subtracting the NBB from the weighted average execution price, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on sell limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the execution price minus the NBB and the execution price minus the limit price.
     
						
						
    Prior to December 7, 2015, price improvement for limit orders (buy and sell) was calculated using the methodology for price improvement on market orders described above.
    
						
						
    For buys and sells, price improvement is displayed per execution and per order, only when an order has been net price improved. Price improvements at the execution and individual order level are rounded down to the nearest penny.
    
							
						
    Price improvement data is not provided for not held orders, all or none orders, sell short orders, and orders placed outside of standard market hours.
    
							
						
    Some orders may not receive any price improvement. Fast market conditions and large order sizes relative to the bid or ask size may result in shares executing at or outside the NBBO. To learn more about our commitment to execution quality, click here.
    
						
						
    To learn more about average price trade reporting, including how to enroll or unenroll, click  here.

						instructions; otherwise, the replacement order will not have specific
						share information.

      Personal Rate of Return is calculated with a time-weighted formula, widely used by financial analysts to calculate investment earnings. The calculated value reflects the result of your investment selections as well as any activity in the plan accounts shown. Other personal rate of return formulas may yield different results. Remember, past performance is no guarantee of future results.
      					
					
      
					
      
						
      Personal Rate of Return information for authorized Fidelity accounts will become available the monthly cycle following authorization. For periods less than one year, performance returns are presented on a cumulative basis.
      
						
      If your return information contains dashes '--', we either don't have a return for that time period, or your account is being validated. Accounts opened after the beginning of the year are excluded from the calculation.
      
						
      Your Personal Rate of Return is calculated using a money-weighted formula. It reflects the performance of the underlying investments in your eligible Fidelity accounts including dividends, interest, and fees; as well as the size and timing of your individual trades. If you use an account with cash management features, the Personal Rate of Return calculation may be affected by deposits, withdrawals, bill payment and other money movement transactions. Non-Fidelity accounts are excluded from the calculation. The Personal Rate of Return is an estimate only and should not be used solely in making investment decisions. It is calculated using Fidelity-provided information and information from third-party data sources and providers and therefore Fidelity cannot make any representations or guarantees as to its timeliness and accuracy. Fidelity will not provide notification that past data may have been inaccurate, or that it has been corrected.
      
						
      Personal Rate of Return (money-weighted) information may not be available for the following account types: Employer-Sponsored Retirement Plans (e.g., 401(k) plans), Brokerage Link accounts, Brokerage Flex accounts, certain insurance/annuity holdings, and stock plans. These accounts are also not included in the Rate of Return calculation for your entire portfolio appearing at the top of the Portfolio Summary page. Time-weighted returns are available for Employer-Sponsored Retirement Plans as of the end of the previous business day and can be accessed by See YTD Change link.
      
						
      Performance calculations include accounts that have been "hidden" since the last performance reporting period. "Hidden" accounts will be removed from all performance calculations during the next monthly update.

      Today's Gain/Loss equals the total dollar change in securities held for the selected accounts identified in the account selector. This balance only factors in securities held and does not include any pending activity (debits/credits) within the selected accounts. The percentage change represents the total dollar change compared to the value of securities held in your accounts, not the total account value.
      
						
      Today's Gain/Loss does not include 529 CIT accounts, Annuity contracts, non-Fidelity accounts, workplace accounts or pension benefits listed in the All Accounts view.
      
						
      For securities priced daily, such as mutual funds, Today's Gain/Loss is calculated using the prior business day's market closing price. For securities priced intraday, Today's Gain/Loss is calculated using the last available price.
      
						
					
      
					
      
						
      Your Balance Over Time reflects the difference in your All Accounts total balance over the selected time period. It includes all gain, loss, deposit and withdrawal activity over the selected time period, as of the most recent market close. This difference is divided by the beginning total balance at the start of the selected time period to calculate the relevant percentage increase or decrease during this time period.

      Your Allocation Style is determined based on the rounded percentage of equity holdings in your selected accounts as follows:
						
        
							
      • if equity % is less than or equal to 10%, then Short Term;
        • 
							
      • if equity % is between 11% - 24%, then Conservative;
        • 
							
      • if equity % is between 25% - 34%, then Moderate With Income;
        • 
							
      • if equity % is between 35% - 44%, then Moderate;
        •  
							
      • if equity % is between 45% - 54%, then Balanced;
        • 
							
      • if equity % is between 55% - 64%, then Growth With Income;
        • 
							
      • if equity % is between 65% - 78%, then Growth;
        • 
							
      • if equity % is between 79% - 92%, then Aggressive Growth;
        • 
							
      • if equity % is greater than or equal to 93% then Most Aggressive;
        • 
						
      
						
      If a large portion of your holdings are identified as Unknown or Other, the percentage of equity holdings in your selected accounts may be low, indicating a low level of risk associated with your portfolio, without consideration of the risks associated with the Unknown and Other assets. As a result, your asset allocation assessment may not accurately reflect the current risks inherent in your selected accounts.

      Long positions are those reported securities holdings held individually or as underlying investments that were fully paid purchases. Short positions are those margin or short positions held individually or as underlying investments that were not fully paid purchases, but instead involved borrowing in order to support the purchase. Note that trades initiated within a money market fund (such as Fidelity Cash Reserves) pending settlement at the close of a calendar month may present as a short position or negative allocation and inadvertently impact the analysis set forth above. The chart provides an approximate indication of these types of holdings.
      
						
      
					
      
					
      
						
      Securities are priced real-time for customers that have agreed to the Real-Time Quotes Subscriber Agreements; otherwise, quotes are delayed at least 15 minutes. If the current market price is unavailable or the market is closed, Fidelity will factor in the most recent closing market price to determine the closing market value. Non-Fidelity account positions totals may differ from the balances shown in your list of accounts because positions are updated more frequently than account balances.
      
						
      When Securities are Priced:
      
						
      Equities and ETFs are typically priced real-time. If the current market price is unavailable or the market is closed, Fidelity will factor in the most recent closing market price to determine the closing market value.
      
						
      Mutual fund positions are priced after the official market close (typically between 5 p.m. and 6 p.m. ET) at which point your account is calculated using the new price and current shares for that position. If a sale or purchase of a mutual fund settles that day, the account value will be calculated using the new quantity the following day. During market open, mutual fund positions are priced as of the previous day's market close.
      
						
      Annuities are priced as of the market close date on which the value per unit, income value, or withdrawal value for an annuity was last calculated. Annuity contract values reported on an individual basis. Click on the individual contract for details.
      
						
      If a trade has recently been made in your Fidelity  Personalized Portfolios account, the value of your positions after market hours may be calculated using the previous day's share quantity and may not accurately reflect the true market value of your positions at this time. Any changes to your position holdings will be updated in your account around 4 AM EST.

      Fidelity will attempt to cancel an open or partially filled order on
						a "best efforts" basis. Because Fidelity is responsible for
						executing an order as promptly as possible upon receipt, your order may
						have been partially or completely filled before the cancellation was
						received and accepted.
      
						
      A single order for a large quantity of shares of a security may be
						filled through multiple executions. In some cases, not all of these
						executions are accessible on this page. To verify if the order has been
						filled in its entirety, please go to the "Positions" page or call a
						trading representative at 1-800-544-6666.
      
						
						
      Price improvement details provided for domestic stock and single leg option orders entered during market hours after the primary opening, provided there is a National Best Bid and Offer (NBBO) at the time the order is placed. Price improvement details are provided for informational purposes only and are not used for regulatory reporting purposes.
       

						
      Buy market orders with a weighted average execution price below the National Best Offer (NBO) are considered price improved. Price improvement for buy market orders is calculated by subtracting the weighted average execution price from the NBO, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on buy limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the NBO minus the execution price and the limit price minus the execution price. Sell market orders with a weighted average execution price above the National Best Bid (NBB) are considered price improved. Price improvement for sell market orders is calculated by subtracting the NBB from the weighted average execution price, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on sell limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the execution price minus the NBB and the execution price minus the limit price.
       
						
						
      Prior to December 7, 2015, price improvement for limit orders (buy and sell) was calculated using the methodology for price improvement on market orders described above.
      
						
						
      For buys and sells, price improvement is displayed per execution and per order, only when an order has been net price improved. Price improvements at the execution and individual order level are rounded down to the nearest penny.
      
							
						
      Price improvement data is not provided for not held orders, all or none orders, sell short orders, and orders placed outside of standard market hours.
      
							
						
      Some orders may not receive any price improvement. Fast market conditions and large order sizes relative to the bid or ask size may result in shares executing at or outside the NBBO. To learn more about our commitment to execution quality, click here.
      
						
						
      To learn more about average price trade reporting, including how to enroll or unenroll, click  here.
